dasel put -t string -v foo -f manifest.yaml -r yaml -s first

dasel delete \
  -t string \
  -v foo \
  -f manifest.yaml \
  -r yaml \
  -w yaml \
  -s 'overall.replaceable_a'


```

in order to access lists within an above key, you have to first convert a yaml to json.

```
% dasel -f manifest.yaml -r yaml -w json
{
  "first": "foo",
  "overall": [
    {
      "name": "example1",
      "replaceable_a": "oldvalue",
      "keep_this": "safe"
    },
    {
      "name": "example2",
      "replaceable_b": "oldvalue",
      "replaceable_c": "oldvalue",
      "something_else": "untouched"
    }
  ]
}
```

So if we want to index something inside we do:

```
% dasel -f manifest.yaml -r yaml -w json | dasel -r json 'overall.[1]'
{
  "name": "example2",
  "replaceable_b": "oldvalue",
  "replaceable_c": "oldvalue",
  "something_else": "untouched"
}
```

OK, actually it does work with yaml now, like so:

```
% dasel -f manifest.yaml -r yaml 'overall.[0]'
name: example1
replaceable_a: oldvalue
keep_this: safe
```